105
00:06:55,603 --> 00:06:59,805
first, get something that feels really, really good for VR

106
00:07:00,125 --> 00:07:03,566
before you start to expand beyond that with your game.

107
00:07:04,387 --> 00:07:08,408
And that's something that in other forms of game development

108
00:07:08,768 --> 00:07:11,769
is kind of taken for granted because the mechanics are

109
00:07:11,830 --> 00:07:12,850
fairly well established.

110
00:07:12,990 --> 00:07:15,271
And you can kind of just brute force everything

111
00:07:15,311 --> 00:07:16,551
at once to a degree.

112
00:07:17,011 --> 00:07:21,193
But in VR, there's so many new areas to design and explore,

113
00:07:21,253 --> 00:07:23,154
so many new technologies that you have to create,

114
00:07:23,494 --> 00:07:26,415
that taking the time to really focus on that core mechanic

115
00:07:26,715 --> 00:07:28,576
before you start to put a metagame around it

116
00:07:29,076 --> 00:07:30,557
is particularly important.

117
00:07:30,617 --> 00:07:31,957
And it served us very, very well.

118
00:07:34,988 --> 00:07:37,991
So then some of the lessons in particular that the team

119
00:07:38,071 --> 00:07:40,673
learned from these early prototypes that we were just

120
00:07:40,713 --> 00:07:41,234
talking about.

121
00:07:41,834 --> 00:07:44,537
One of those big lessons is the difference between realism

122
00:07:44,637 --> 00:07:46,439
versus usability.

123
00:07:46,859 --> 00:07:49,081
So a lot of people, in particular in the early days,

124
00:07:49,102 --> 00:07:52,124
and even now, still in VR, one of their major focuses is I

125
00:07:52,164 --> 00:07:55,668
want to recreate real life verbatim exactly in VR.

126
00:07:56,108 --> 00:07:59,151
And sometimes that works well, and a lot of times it doesn't.

127
00:07:59,872 --> 00:08:01,795
Because at the end of the day, at least, what we're trying to

128
00:08:01,835 --> 00:08:04,538
do is make great game experiences.

129
00:08:04,598 --> 00:08:07,723
So one great example here that we have up on the screen is,

130
00:08:07,743 --> 00:08:10,126
again, going back to Bullet Time Apex, the team initially

131
00:08:10,707 --> 00:08:12,769
made a shotgun amongst many of the other weapons that they

132
00:08:12,789 --> 00:08:15,873
made, and they had stock on the shotgun and on the other

133
00:08:15,914 --> 00:08:16,594
weapons and such.

134
00:08:16,975 --> 00:08:19,616
trying to create that impression of reality.

135
00:08:19,917 --> 00:08:21,738
But actually once we got that into the game

136
00:08:21,858 --> 00:08:24,019
and players were actually holding the weapons in their hands,

137
00:08:24,039 --> 00:08:27,321
they realized that because you don't have anything physically pushing against you,

138
00:08:27,341 --> 00:08:29,283
this is actually causing a problem.

139
00:08:29,343 --> 00:08:32,264
This actually wasn't helping gameplay, it was hindering it.

140
00:08:32,345 --> 00:08:35,006
Because already just having to hold a weapon with two hands,

141
00:08:35,406 --> 00:08:36,907
there's already a slight disconnect there.

142
00:08:37,828 --> 00:08:39,469
Especially with a two-handed weapon like a shotgun.

143
00:08:39,609 --> 00:08:42,431
Adding the third element of something that you're supposed to brace against yourself,

144
00:08:42,771 --> 00:08:43,572
it just didn't work out.

145
00:08:43,932 --> 00:08:47,494
And you can see how that evolved in our raw data picture of Boss,

146
00:08:47,534 --> 00:08:49,555
that he no longer has a stock on the shotgun.

147
00:08:49,595 --> 00:08:51,717
Specifically, we redesigned the weapon.

148
00:08:51,757 --> 00:08:55,699
We really enjoyed the weapon, but we took that off of it to make it more friendly to gameplay.

149
00:08:55,719 --> 00:09:00,042
Because at the end of the day, that's what we're trying to create, is amazing gameplay experiences.

150
00:09:01,030 --> 00:09:05,993
And you'll notice with all of the weapons in raw data, they are a little bit larger than life.

151
00:09:06,193 --> 00:09:08,155
And again, this goes to the usability factor.

152
00:09:09,395 --> 00:09:14,278
We really wanted it to feel good, to be just really slick to use,

153
00:09:14,538 --> 00:09:19,882
and to really get into using the weapon and not have to fumble with the realities of using a weapon.

154
00:09:20,522 --> 00:09:24,925
So this is one of the early key learnings that really influenced the rest of our development.

155
00:09:27,845 --> 00:09:37,156
So then probably the next biggest pillar that as a studio, in particular on raw data, the team really focused on was the concept of active VR.

156
00:09:37,657 --> 00:09:42,322
And we were constantly asking ourselves, what is active VR? What are we trying to do here? What are we trying to accomplish?

157
00:09:42,422 --> 00:09:44,244
And with our products, our experiences,

158
00:09:44,825 --> 00:09:46,326
We really don't want to just sell immersion.

159
00:09:46,366 --> 00:09:50,550
Immersion is great, but we also want to sell that active experience.

160
00:09:50,611 --> 00:09:54,054
Because we find, for the most part, there's a lot of great VR other products out there.

161
00:09:54,094 --> 00:09:54,855
Fantastic stuff.

162
00:09:54,875 --> 00:09:57,437
But we find the VR products that get you to move your body.

163
00:09:57,877 --> 00:09:58,938
To get you to move around.

164
00:09:59,539 --> 00:10:02,041
Whether you're using two guns pointing in different directions.

165
00:10:02,061 --> 00:10:04,344
Whether you're having to dodge enemies trying to hit you.

166
00:10:04,404 --> 00:10:06,626
Whether you're having to physically interact with objects.

167
00:10:07,006 --> 00:10:09,288
The more we can get the player to move into VR,

168
00:10:09,328 --> 00:10:10,970
the more physically active we can get,

169
00:10:11,330 --> 00:10:13,412
for the most part we find players have more fun.

170
00:10:13,993 --> 00:10:16,595
So as much as possible, a big focus for raw data

171
00:10:16,995 --> 00:10:20,138
was get players moving, make it an active VR experience.

172
00:10:20,178 --> 00:10:22,200
Because to us, that really was the dream,

173
00:10:22,460 --> 00:10:23,661
that's what we were focusing on,

174
00:10:24,182 --> 00:10:26,964
is really what Active Bring Art sucks you into that experience.

175
00:10:28,142 --> 00:10:34,506
So, and part of this was just getting the closer that we could get the world to the player, the better.

176
00:10:34,626 --> 00:10:38,389
So enemies are a little bit larger and imposing, they get right up in your face.

177
00:10:39,069 --> 00:10:41,331
We spent time with the robot enemies in the game.

178
00:10:41,991 --> 00:10:44,493
You know, we really get them up close and personal with you,

179
00:10:44,793 --> 00:10:48,095
just so that you can really get a sense of that immersion and being part of the world.

180
00:10:48,415 --> 00:10:52,598
As opposed to having them stay far back and do long-range kind of interactions.

181
00:10:53,058 --> 00:10:54,840
We certainly have some of that, but...

182
00:10:55,300 --> 00:10:57,803
But we did, we toned that down. That's an excellent point.

183
00:10:57,843 --> 00:11:00,806
In particular, I don't know how you have played the game or have noticed,

184
00:11:00,846 --> 00:11:04,529
but another example of that, besides enemies shooting at you far away,

185
00:11:04,590 --> 00:11:07,012
again, we find the closer we bring the enemies to you,

186
00:11:07,112 --> 00:11:10,315
the more in your space they are, the more fun it becomes, the more real it becomes.

187
00:11:10,815 --> 00:11:11,596
The more immersive it is.

