00:13:09,690 --> 00:13:13,532
where you can communicate with other players before you actually get into matches. And

225
00:13:13,572 --> 00:13:17,615
it's something that we will continue to build around. It's something that really shouldn't

226
00:13:17,655 --> 00:13:24,739
be overlooked because with VR especially, the market is so new and growing that if you can

227
00:13:24,779 --> 00:13:28,342
bring people together in any way, whether it's co-op or through other types of social

228
00:13:28,382 --> 00:13:33,605
interactions, it only helps the entire industry and it helps with word of mouth for your game.

229
00:13:34,465 --> 00:13:38,429
For anybody who's done work in the mobile space and the social mobile space,

230
00:13:38,450 --> 00:13:43,775
you may be familiar with the K-factor equation and how if you get somebody in your game

231
00:13:43,815 --> 00:13:48,480
and they're talking about it and they can share it with friends, that then increases your reach.

232
00:13:48,880 --> 00:13:50,662
And we're finding the same type of thing here.

233
00:13:50,802 --> 00:13:56,928
So social VR, active VR, both were very important early core tenets for Servios and raw data.

234
00:13:57,028 --> 00:14:00,431
Yeah, definitely. And you can see that in the way people play the game in particular.

235
00:14:01,691 --> 00:14:06,214
As Chris said, we didn't shy away from it early on. We believed, we still truly believe,

236
00:14:06,675 --> 00:14:11,438
social experiences in VR can be greater than any other game or platform that's out there right now.

237
00:14:12,058 --> 00:14:17,021
As much as it's really fun, whether you're sitting on the couch with a friend, or you're on the internet and talking to them,

238
00:14:17,081 --> 00:14:19,043
or typing with them, whether it's on a headset or not,

239
00:14:19,623 --> 00:14:22,445
There's just something magical about being in VR,

240
00:14:22,786 --> 00:14:25,488
and when you're playing a game and the person materializes in front of you,

241
00:14:25,548 --> 00:14:27,790
and he's moving his arms, and he's talking to you,

242
00:14:27,850 --> 00:14:29,551
and you're looking at him and he's looking at you.

