00:14:36,698 --> 00:14:40,000
is a much more social experience than in any other platform to date.

246
00:14:40,461 --> 00:14:40,581
Great.

247
00:14:43,079 --> 00:14:48,743
So what happened next? Around this time we showed the game off at VRLA and GDC last year,

248
00:14:48,823 --> 00:14:54,628
got tremendous feedback, and realized that we really had a strong core game to build upon.

249
00:14:55,008 --> 00:15:00,011
But we also realized that we needed something more than what was just a set of core mechanics,

250
00:15:00,112 --> 00:15:05,736
right? As great as they were, we needed more than what could be labeled a sort of a demo experience.

251
00:15:05,776 --> 00:15:06,696
We wanted something that

252
00:15:07,237 --> 00:15:11,478
Really did embrace the AAA premium game sort of moniker

253
00:15:11,798 --> 00:15:14,298
that we could go with premium pricing on and all these things

254
00:15:14,358 --> 00:15:17,539
and something that would provide a full gameplay loop for the players.

255
00:15:18,099 --> 00:15:22,560
So, this is the time when the metagame sort of made its way into the game.

256
00:15:23,021 --> 00:15:26,501
Mike did a great job with several elements as did James,

257
00:15:26,901 --> 00:15:30,562
putting in a strong narrative, you got a sense of that in the trailer.

258
00:15:30,942 --> 00:15:33,903
Can't understate how important that is to bringing the world to life.

259
00:15:35,384 --> 00:15:38,267
Also introducing things like a nexus and tower defense.

260
00:15:38,768 --> 00:15:39,709
If you want to talk about any of that.

261
00:15:39,789 --> 00:15:41,651
Other mechanics, I think that's a good point too.

262
00:15:41,991 --> 00:15:45,916
There are fantastic other VR experiences out there.

263
00:15:45,936 --> 00:15:49,720
I mean, we download them and play them all just like everybody else and have a great time with them.

264
00:15:50,280 --> 00:15:54,665
But a lot of the experiences, while they're a lot of fun, they're short experiences, right?

265
00:15:54,685 --> 00:15:55,586
They'll last a good, you know,

266
00:15:56,707 --> 00:15:57,567
15, 20 minutes, maybe an hour.

267
00:15:58,067 --> 00:16:00,688
And we knew with raw data that wasn't enough for us.

268
00:16:00,728 --> 00:16:02,848
We didn't want people just playing once, twice,

269
00:16:02,908 --> 00:16:04,228
or for two hours.

270
00:16:04,248 --> 00:16:06,269
We wanted them to get a full eight, 10 plus.

271
00:16:06,309 --> 00:16:09,029
I mean, hell, we have some people that have 50 plus hours

272
00:16:09,109 --> 00:16:09,629
on raw data.

273
00:16:09,689 --> 00:16:10,249
It's incredible.

274
00:16:10,870 --> 00:16:12,690
But that was a big focus for us, is

275
00:16:12,750 --> 00:16:15,010
to make sure we had an experience that players could

276
00:16:15,050 --> 00:16:16,691
keep coming back to in VR.

277
00:16:17,031 --> 00:16:18,751
And that every time we release new content,

278
00:16:18,771 --> 00:16:20,792
there's always a reason for them to keep coming back,

279
00:16:21,072 --> 00:16:23,592
to try it out, try something new, and experience something

280
00:16:23,773 --> 00:16:27,213
A lot of replay value that you don't typically get a lot of the other experiences right now.

281
00:16:29,923 --> 00:16:31,644
Then, so, moving on to locomotion.

282
00:16:31,664 --> 00:16:34,606
That was another big thing we had to figure out from the beginning.

283
00:16:35,087 --> 00:16:36,588
So, for those of you who have played Raw Data,

284
00:16:36,668 --> 00:16:38,509
or for those of you who haven't, we have a slide here

285
00:16:38,589 --> 00:16:40,831
showing you the concept of what we call tele-shifting.

286
00:16:40,871 --> 00:16:42,552
So, we knew from the beginning,

287
00:16:42,592 --> 00:16:45,774
actually the very first demo the team had of Raw Data,

288
00:16:46,175 --> 00:16:47,576
characters were stationary.

289
00:16:47,816 --> 00:16:51,578
Not that they couldn't move, but you had your platform in the center

290
00:16:51,699 --> 00:16:53,420
and you had your both characters in co-op,

291
00:16:53,440 --> 00:16:55,661
but you were kind of stuck to wherever you could physically walk to.

292
00:16:56,602 --> 00:16:59,724
And that was a really fun starting experience, a great prototype.

293
00:16:59,745 --> 00:17:04,028
We were really focused on the gameplay, the guns, the shooting, the melee and all that.

294
00:17:04,628 --> 00:17:06,430
We just felt it was too limiting.

295
00:17:06,450 --> 00:17:08,231
We knew from the beginning this was just too limiting.

296
00:17:08,251 --> 00:17:10,113
We wanted players to explore the environment.

297
00:17:10,153 --> 00:17:14,616
We have these amazing artists who are making all these fantastic props and models and everything

298
00:17:14,636 --> 00:17:15,837
in these incredible environments.

299
00:17:16,358 --> 00:17:18,639
And you were restricted, you couldn't see them.

300
00:17:18,719 --> 00:17:21,121
And it also really hampered gameplay.

301
00:17:21,462 --> 00:17:24,703
I mean, the fact that an enemy would back up or you want to

302
00:17:24,763 --> 00:17:26,444
run to him rather than wait for him to come to you.

303
00:17:26,924 --> 00:17:28,865
So we knew from the beginning we really needed to have

304
00:17:28,925 --> 00:17:30,225
locomotion as part of that.

305
00:17:30,265 --> 00:17:31,866
We couldn't accept stationary.

306
00:17:31,906 --> 00:17:34,687
We didn't see a full game coming out of just stationary.

307
00:17:35,107 --> 00:17:37,348
So that's when we focused on the solution for

308
00:17:37,428 --> 00:17:37,988
tele-shifting.

309
00:17:38,028 --> 00:17:41,029
The reason why we went this route for raw data, at least

310
00:17:41,049 --> 00:17:44,231
our first product released, is that we wanted to ensure there

311
00:17:44,251 --> 00:17:44,811
was no nausea.

312
00:17:45,151 --> 00:17:46,752
That was a big belief from the beginning.

313
00:17:46,892 --> 00:17:50,033
We make experiences that do not make people sick in any capacity.

314
00:17:50,513 --> 00:17:52,734
Everyone should be able to enjoy it and have an amazing time.

315
00:17:53,094 --> 00:17:55,275
So this is where we're working with a lot of coders,

316
00:17:55,295 --> 00:17:58,576
working with Alex in particular as a tech lead on the project,

317
00:17:58,896 --> 00:18:01,697
really hammering down how we make this teleshifting experience work.

318
00:18:02,237 --> 00:18:03,338
One, it doesn't make players sick.

319
00:18:03,838 --> 00:18:06,179
Two, it's very rapid, it's very easy to use.

320
00:18:06,519 --> 00:18:09,240
And then three, it allows you to feel like you're in the environment.

321
00:18:09,280 --> 00:18:10,321
Too many of the earlier...

322
00:18:11,461 --> 00:18:14,707
VR experiences we've played with the teleporting experiences,

323
00:18:14,747 --> 00:18:16,691
it felt like you were kind of blinking in and out of existence.

324
00:18:16,731 --> 00:18:19,776
And we wanted to make it feel like you were actually moving from one location to another.

325
00:18:20,297 --> 00:18:23,082
So all of those reasons we spent a lot of time focusing on this feature.

326
00:18:25,966 --> 00:18:28,368
And then moving on to the next big pillar.

327
00:18:28,408 --> 00:18:32,732
So this is actually a lot of the conversations to define what raw data was from the beginning.

328
00:18:33,613 --> 00:18:36,756
So going back to Bullet Time Apex, the early prototype the team had,

329
00:18:37,136 --> 00:18:41,340
they solved great mechanics for how to interact with things, how to use weapons,

330
00:18:42,040 --> 00:18:45,323
how to be in the VR space, solved so many problems.

331
00:18:45,744 --> 00:18:48,205
But the early prototypes we had when we were playing,

332
00:18:48,225 --> 00:18:49,346
it was like, well, this is fun.

333
00:18:49,386 --> 00:18:51,447
I can use a shotgun, I can use a bow, I can use a pistol.

334
00:18:52,267 --> 00:18:53,808
But I can go do that in real life, right?

335
00:18:53,848 --> 00:18:56,170
I can go do a shooting range or experience those things.

336
00:18:56,210 --> 00:18:57,471
I can't fight robots in real life.

337
00:18:57,491 --> 00:18:58,171
That's unfortunate.

338
00:18:58,831 --> 00:18:59,472
Maybe in the future.

339
00:19:00,252 --> 00:19:03,334
But that was the big thing for myself joining the team early

340
00:19:03,454 --> 00:19:06,316
on is making sure, well, this is cool, but I want more, right?

341
00:19:06,776 --> 00:19:11,881
I'm in VR to do something that I just can't experience in real life, that promise of VR, right?

342
00:19:12,281 --> 00:19:16,085
And to me, for Raw Data, that means being that hero, being that badass character.

343
00:19:16,545 --> 00:19:23,211
We all have our favorite heroes or superheroes, whether it's the Avengers or someone from a sci-fi movie, or aliens, or any of these things.

344
00:19:23,652 --> 00:19:26,695
And we wanted you to live that experience, right?

345
00:19:28,176 --> 00:19:31,838
the movie, you're in your favorite book, you're in your favorite TV show. So that was a huge

346
00:19:31,878 --> 00:19:36,620
focus from the beginning to adding powers, adding abilities, amping it up, taking this

347
00:19:36,860 --> 00:19:40,261
above and beyond just the basic weapons which are already very fun.

348
00:19:41,882 --> 00:19:48,145
So that gave us an incredibly rich full game with which to work on and in order to get

349
00:19:48,225 --> 00:19:52,707
there, to accomplish all of these things, we really had to step back while the team,

350
00:19:52,727 --> 00:19:56,908
the majority of the team was off at GDC, showing off the game.

351
00:19:58,229 --> 00:20:02,609
The production team stayed back and really dug through the scope of the game.

352
00:20:02,669 --> 00:20:04,090
We did that with the leads as well.

353
00:20:04,630 --> 00:20:10,851
And we took the time, we took a couple of weeks to really hone down what the scope and the schedule was

354
00:20:11,371 --> 00:20:15,692
with the goal of as soon as the team was back from GDC and had settled back in

355
00:20:16,072 --> 00:20:19,053
that we had an entire road map that would get us to early access

356
00:20:19,493 --> 00:20:24,134
and would really encompass all of these core mechanics and the metagame features

357
00:20:24,814 --> 00:20:25,914
in a way that we could get there.

358
00:20:26,954 --> 00:20:29,777
So that was pretty important for us. Up until this point raw

359
00:20:29,817 --> 00:20:32,961
data had been in production for about two years. So we had

360
00:20:34,140 --> 00:20:37,502
eight months or so, I would say. We were about a year altogether before we went into early

361
00:20:37,602 --> 00:20:43,005
access. So this was just good in getting the team on the same page. Sort of the takeaway

362
00:20:43,065 --> 00:20:50,188
here is that we used GDC, the time that most of the team was away, as an opportunity to

363
00:20:50,228 --> 00:20:55,631
hunker down and do some of the more production wonky stuff and build out the schedule. And

364
00:20:55,671 --> 00:20:58,272
that way the team was able to come back and hit the ground running.

365
00:20:58,652 --> 00:21:02,138
So being able to find those natural breaks that your team

366
00:21:02,178 --> 00:21:05,223
is already focused on something else is a great way to keep the

367
00:21:05,263 --> 00:21:08,549
momentum going where you don't have to sit idle while you're

368
00:21:08,769 --> 00:21:10,312
re-scoping or figuring out schedules.

369
00:21:14,073 --> 00:21:15,614
So we had our schedule.

370
00:21:16,114 --> 00:21:16,755
We were on track.

371
00:21:16,995 --> 00:21:19,977
We got ready to launch the game into early access.

372
00:21:20,298 --> 00:21:23,320
And we then had to decide what would our launch timing be.

373
00:21:24,020 --> 00:21:25,882
So sounds like a simple question.

374
00:21:25,942 --> 00:21:26,462
The game's ready.

375
00:21:26,502 --> 00:21:27,303
You just launch it.

376
00:21:27,503 --> 00:21:29,124
Well, we could have done that.

377
00:21:29,945 --> 00:21:32,847
We also could have launched it over 4th of July weekend,

378
00:21:32,907 --> 00:21:33,908
a long weekend.

379
00:21:34,028 --> 00:21:35,289
Seems like that might make sense.

380
00:21:35,389 --> 00:21:37,790
People have extra time to play games if they're not

381
00:21:37,831 --> 00:21:38,551
with their families.

382
00:21:40,252 --> 00:21:45,177
Or we could try to do something else. So one of the things that we really believe in at

383
00:21:45,217 --> 00:21:51,804
Servios as well is not only do you look inward, but you can look outward for guidance. So

384
00:21:51,924 --> 00:21:57,029
what does that mean? In this case we reached out to our platform partners and we reached

385
00:21:57,089 --> 00:21:59,511
out to hardware partners that we had been working with.

386
00:21:59,872 --> 00:22:02,533
And we involved them in the conversation around launch timing.

387
00:22:03,253 --> 00:22:05,634
And, you know, why would you do that, you may ask?

388
00:22:05,714 --> 00:22:14,559
Well, it was really helpful for us because we were advised that our existing plans would have had us come out during the middle of the Steam summer sale.

389
00:22:15,379 --> 00:22:22,563
And if we were to do that, there is no way that we could have received any sort of support from the Steam store around launch.

390
00:22:22,983 --> 00:22:26,205
Not that there was any guarantee that we would get support if we launched later.

391
00:22:26,645 --> 00:22:31,009
But there was definitely a guarantee we would get nothing if we launched during the summer sale.

392
00:22:31,429 --> 00:22:35,493
So we would have walked right into a situation where we just would have shot ourselves in the foot

393
00:22:35,733 --> 00:22:39,637
in the sense of partners being able to help promote for us.

394
00:22:40,198 --> 00:22:42,780
So I really recommend whenever you're looking to launch...

395
00:22:44,000 --> 00:22:48,864
Not only look inwardly, but talk to your partners, your platform partners in particular.

396
00:22:49,565 --> 00:22:51,767
And develop that relationship.

397
00:22:51,847 --> 00:22:52,908
Don't just speak with them.

398
00:22:53,408 --> 00:22:57,992
When you're ready to launch, we tend to visit with our partners at least once a quarter,

399
00:22:58,392 --> 00:22:59,053
if not more.

400
00:22:59,273 --> 00:23:00,234
Get some face time.

401
00:23:00,915 --> 00:23:03,457
No one ever wants to see you only when you're asking for something.

402
00:23:04,017 --> 00:23:06,520
So I probably belabored that point.

403
00:23:06,580 --> 00:23:09,162
Yeah, but I think that's the important thing to acknowledge,

404
00:23:09,222 --> 00:23:11,083
that VR in particular right now,

405
00:23:11,223 --> 00:23:14,906
it's not as mainstream as giant console games

406
00:23:14,946 --> 00:23:17,147
with enormous budgets that are going to be at Walmart

407
00:23:17,167 --> 00:23:19,249
and Target, and to not fight that,

408
00:23:19,289 --> 00:23:20,510
to just embrace it and accept it

409
00:23:20,570 --> 00:23:23,492
as a much more of an indie atmosphere and mindset.

410
00:23:23,532 --> 00:23:26,994
So having those relationships with your partners,

411
00:23:27,074 --> 00:23:30,237
whether it's on Steam or the Oculus Store or PlayStation,

412
00:23:30,257 --> 00:23:31,958
however, whatever approach that you're going,

413
00:23:32,538 --> 00:23:33,699
it's very important you acknowledge

414
00:23:33,799 --> 00:23:35,300
how your users are going to find you.

415
00:23:35,840 --> 00:23:39,942
And making sure that there's a time window where your partners can help them find you.

416
00:23:39,982 --> 00:23:43,923
Because it's very much an explorative driven system at this point.

417
00:23:44,123 --> 00:23:45,043
Well said. Well said.

418
00:23:45,563 --> 00:23:49,264
So now that we had our launch timing we had to figure out what price should we sell the game at.

419
00:23:49,704 --> 00:23:51,385
And again we had several options here.

420
00:23:51,485 --> 00:23:54,706
We looked around at what was happening in the market.

421
00:23:55,146 --> 00:23:56,586
We could price at the same...

422
00:23:57,167 --> 00:23:59,929
the sort of range that most of the other games were priced at.

423
00:24:00,710 --> 00:24:03,752
We could go for something lower, we could go for something higher.

424
00:24:04,192 --> 00:24:06,434
We had a lot of debate and discussion internally.

425
00:24:06,534 --> 00:24:10,818
We also enlisted the aid of our partners and decided in the end

426
00:24:10,958 --> 00:24:14,341
to pursue a premium pricing model because we,

427
00:24:14,421 --> 00:24:16,262
not only did we really believe in the product.

428
00:24:17,103 --> 00:24:18,905
that we had a premium level product.

429
00:24:19,305 --> 00:24:21,167
We saw some of the supply and demand

430
00:24:21,747 --> 00:24:23,709
that was playing out within the marketplace,

431
00:24:23,729 --> 00:24:26,051
that there was a vacuum for the premium content pricing.

432
00:24:26,532 --> 00:24:29,275
But if you looked at the demographics of the users,

433
00:24:29,315 --> 00:24:31,216
they tended to be on the higher end,

434
00:24:31,256 --> 00:24:32,878
people that could afford premium pricing

435
00:24:32,998 --> 00:24:34,019
for the right product.

436
00:24:34,980 --> 00:24:39,022
And you can never raise your price once you've set it.

437
00:24:39,042 --> 00:24:42,804
It's just a simple pricing dynamic, but you can always come down, you can do sales.

438
00:24:43,165 --> 00:24:47,127
So it gave us room to work in case the market did not respond the way that we thought it would.

439
00:24:47,607 --> 00:24:51,729
Fortunately it did, and not only did it respond as we thought,

440
00:24:51,769 --> 00:24:54,251
it responded much better than we could have hoped for.

441
00:24:54,651 --> 00:24:57,793
And I think that's also just a choice internally we made is we

442
00:24:57,893 --> 00:25:00,915
wanted to make a premium product, right? It's us. We

443
00:25:00,955 --> 00:25:03,938
could have made smaller, bite-sized products, right? But

444
00:25:03,958 --> 00:25:06,359
we specifically were acknowledging we wanted to make

445
00:25:06,419 --> 00:25:09,481
a full game for our users, right? Something that they would

446
00:25:09,501 --> 00:25:13,204
cherish. And clearly the market wants this content. They want

447
00:25:13,224 --> 00:25:16,806
premium content. So you want to talk quickly about updates?

448
00:25:17,371 --> 00:25:20,152
Yeah, so just to talk a little bit about this, I know we're

449
00:25:20,192 --> 00:25:23,212
running short on time here. So starting at the beginning we

450
00:25:23,272 --> 00:25:25,493
knew we made the conscious choice as a team. We wanted to

451
00:25:25,533 --> 00:25:28,394
do early access. A lot of this is because we just didn't know

452
00:25:28,734 --> 00:25:31,034
how the community was going to respond, just to be totally

453
00:25:31,054 --> 00:25:35,255
honest. Brand new hardware, brand new systems for everybody.

454
00:25:35,315 --> 00:25:38,016
We had to figure that out. So we released early and then

455
00:25:39,136 --> 00:25:41,958
We started getting feedback right away from the community, which is fantastic.

456
00:25:42,138 --> 00:25:48,182
And let me tell you, the team bent over backwards to respond to the community as fast as it possibly could.

457
00:25:48,242 --> 00:25:52,285
Not just with hot fixes for bugs, but for additional features, little tweaks here and there.

458
00:25:52,846 --> 00:25:57,409
Our coders, our artists, our designers all stayed really late and worked their butts off.

459
00:25:57,429 --> 00:26:01,271
And then we quickly realized we were burning the team out, responding too rapidly to consumers.

460
00:26:01,331 --> 00:26:06,355
And while we were making a few people here and there really happy, it was hurting the longevity of the product.

461
00:26:06,675 --> 00:26:10,097
And we knew we wanted to, again, premium content, premium product.

462
00:26:10,477 --> 00:26:11,878
So we had to space that out.

463
00:26:11,958 --> 00:26:16,020
Instead of going from releasing every two weeks to at some point releasing once a month,

464
00:26:16,060 --> 00:26:19,862
to eventually we realized we wanted to put a bulk of the content together and release it every three months.

465
00:26:20,242 --> 00:26:23,504
Because no matter how we did it, every time you release there's a price you have to pay,

466
00:26:23,524 --> 00:26:24,965
an internal production price, right?

467
00:26:25,325 --> 00:26:27,326
Fixing bugs, stabilizing, optimizing.

468
00:26:27,446 --> 00:26:29,147
So the further we could space that out,

469
00:26:29,207 --> 00:26:30,488
the more efficient the team became.

470
00:26:30,528 --> 00:26:33,349
And honestly, the bigger bang of content releases

471
00:26:33,589 --> 00:26:34,910
